The Ukraine on the path to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and they will never meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
Although the Ukraine is undoubtedly in the East, it is in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path to that goal was, however, not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the Soviet era.
It goes without saying that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine has in connecting with Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural regions were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet style.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We completely messed up the reforms on our own.
Because often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict respect for human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy - in a diluted form, and thought this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
This is evident on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers allow pedestrians to cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to navigate safely around reckless drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a vibrant café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
Young people are learning English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the Internet in Internet cafés.
But these are only the whimsical distractions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the professional politician, which I am, sees more profound changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total opposition to reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
At first, the reform of the state aroused a hostile sentiment both among bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of officials in the public service began.
It was a "one-size-fits-all" reform: the state must shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by wielding the red pen led us to the second stage of our reform process.
The state was gradually reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
Thus, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At first, the authority transferred to these new areas was somewhat too broad to enable them to perform their work effectively.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes complain about these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (although reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of which there are still too many among us - can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but nevertheless a province.
This shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial can never admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open ourselves to the best of what others can offer.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians had to realize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have perhaps contributed to becoming even more sick, but the recently held elections, which deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the edge of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders, or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginal figures.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, hardship-filled journey toward Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and to survive.
